                  ANN 
                  WALTON
               <interp inst="t18300415-228-person2001" type="surname" value="WALTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-228-person2001" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-228-person2001" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a servant to 
               <persName id="t18300415-228-person2002">
                  Jane 
                  Louisa Shee
               <interp inst="t18300415-228-person2002" type="surname" value="Louisa Shee"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-228-person2002" type="given" value="Jane"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-228-person2002" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            ; who lives in <placeName id="t18300415-228-crimeloc1262">Southampton-row, Russell-square</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-228-crimeloc1262" type="placeName" value="Southampton-row, Russell-square"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-228-crimeloc1262" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-228-off1260 t18300415-228-crimeloc1262"></join>. On the 4th of March, about half-past nine o'clock in the morning, I went out, and left the street door ajar - I returned in less than five minutes, and saw the prisoner open the street door wider, and run out with the silver pint mug and cruet-stand in his hand - I knew them to be my mistress', and took them from him; I had left them on the sideboard in the front parlour - I do not know whether the parlour door was shut; he struggled, and struck me before I could get them from him - when I had got them I let go of him; he got away, but recollecting there was more plate where this was, I called Stop thief! I went in, shut the door, and did not see him taken - he was brought back by the witness in two or three minutes; I know him again quite well.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. Did you know him before? A. No.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-228-person2003">
                  STEPHEN 
                  FREWER
               <interp inst="t18300415-228-person2003" type="surname" value="FREWER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-228-person2003" type="given" value="STEPHEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-228-person2003" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a harness-maker, and live in Marchmont-place, Little Coram-street. I heard Walton scream, and saw her struggling with the prisoner on the step - I saw him get from her, and followed him: I lost sight of him for a moment only, and saw him stopped by a man - I took him back to the house, and am sure he is the man.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. He had turned the corner? A. Yes.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-228-person2004">
